*/

#include <cctype> // defines the functions isdigit(), islower(), etc.
#include <cstdlib> // rand(), RAND_MAX const, exit()
#include <ctime> // defines the time() function
//#include <time.h> // use this if <ctime> is not recognized
#include <cfloat>
#include <iomanip> // defines setw()
#include <cmath> // defines pow() and log(), fabs(), sqrt()
#include <iostream> // defines cin and cout
using namespace std; 

int main()
{ int n=44;
  cout << "n = " << n << endl;    // prints the value of n
  cout << "&n = " << &n << endl;  // prints the address of n
}

/*
OUPUT: 
n = 44
&n = 0x0064fdf0

The output shows that the address of n is 0x0064fdf0. You can tell that the output 0x0064fdf0
must be an address because it is given in hexadecimal form, identified by its 0x prefix. The decimal form
for this number is 6,618,608.

Displaying the address of a variable this way is not very useful. The reference operator & has
other more important uses. We saw one use in Folio 5: designating reference parameters in a
function declaration. That use is closely tied to another: declaring reference variables.
*/
